solution.p:
The y-coordinate of the point P is -5, and r = 6, so \sin (\theta) = \dfrac{y}{r} = \dfrac{-5}{6} To find the x-coordinate of P, we use the equation of a circle of radius 6, x^2 + y^2 = 36.
    x^2 + (-5)^2 \amp = 36
    x^2 \amp = 36 - 25 = 11
    x \amp = \pm \sqrt{11}
Because P is in the third quadrant, x = -\sqrt{11}. Thus, \cos (\theta) = \dfrac{x}{r} = \dfrac{-\sqrt{11}}{6}~~~~ \text{and} ~~~~\tan (\theta) = \dfrac{y}{x} = \dfrac{-5}{-\sqrt{11}} = \dfrac{5}{\sqrt{11}}

